A Dutch team of 10 scientists, writing in BioRxiv on March 11, said they had just obtained a full human monoclonal antibody that neutralizes COVID-19. It is the first known antibody that blocks coronavirus infection and could open new possibilities for the prevention and treatment of new pneumonia.

"For the new coronavirus to establish effective infection, it must use a protein called a spike protein to bind to receptors in human cells. The monoclonal antibody is aimed at the spike proteins that inhibit the interaction between the virus and the cell,"lead author Dr Li Wentao, a Chinese scientist, told interface news.

Li is now a researcher in the virus division of the Department of biomolecular health sciences at the University of Utrecht in the Netherlands. The team of 10 scientists, all from the Erasmus Medical Center in Rotterdam and the Utrecht University. In addition to Li, the team also includes a Chinese scientist, Wang Chunyan. The study was led by Dutch scientist Bost-jan Bosch.

Li Wentao has long been concerned about the development of therapeutic antibodies against coronavirus. He told Interface News, "In addition to treating infected patients, antibodies can also be used to prevent viral infections in people at high risk of infection, such as health care workers. If we can successfully enter the clinical, can effectively improve the level of critical and critical care, reduce the mortality rate."

By contrast, "The vaccine is primarily protective for healthy people, but it takes a long time to develop and is relatively slow to work. Chemical drugs such as Redesavir are mainly used to treat infected patients and have an anti-viral effect by inhibiting the replication of the virus, the whole process takes more than 10 months.

The paper has now been submitted to the journal Nature and the peer-reviewed results are expected within the next month. If the peer review is approved, it is hoped to enter the clinical trial process soon.

Li Wentao introduced that his laboratory has been carrying out research on coronavirus for more than 30 years and has accumulated a lot of materials. They began building a special technology platform seven years ago to respond quickly to new viruses. The lab already had the antibody two years ago.

"after the new coronavirus outbreak, the team quickly established a platform related to the new coronavirus research based on the existing technical platform and tested the antibody's ability to neutralize the new coronavirus, which all happened in the last two months, " Li said.

A few years ago, says Frank Grosveld, a professor of cell biology at Erasmus Medical Center in Rotterdam and another leader of the study, in an interview with the university's Erasmus Magazine, they have run the zoonosis Initiative, which aims to develop antibodies against Mers, SARS-CoV and another human coronavirus, HcoV-OC43. At the time, they found antibodies that cross-reacted with the three different viruses and prevented infection. After the outbreak, they used untested antibody samples that remained at the time to select antibodies that only responded to the SARS Cov Mutation and test whether they also responded to SARS-CoV cov-2. Finally, the antibody that blocks SARS-CoV-2 was found.

GROSVENOR also mentioned another use for the antibody: It could be used to create a diagnostic test for new coronavirus pneumonia. This allows people to be tested at home, making it easy to know if they have the virus. If it goes ahead, it will also greatly improve the testing capabilities of European countries.

Grosvenor says they are in discussions with a pharmaceutical company that has the capacity to produce pharmaceutical antibodies on a large scale. But he stressed that the antibody must undergo extensive toxicological testing before entering the market, a process they have already begun.
